a \in \mathbb{R }
\lim_{n \rightarrow \infty}n(a^{\frac{1}{n}}-1)=\log a
\lim\limits_{n \rightarrow \infty}ne^{(\frac{1}{n}\log a)}-n
x = 1/n
 \frac{a^x-1}{x} = \frac{e^{x \log(a)} - 1}{x} = \frac{1 + x \log(a) + R(x \log a) -1}{x} = \log (a) + \log a \left[\frac{R(x \log a)}{x \log a} \right] 
 \frac{R(x \log a)}{x \log a} \rightarrow 0 \text { as } x\rightarrow 0
e^{\theta} = 1 + \theta + R(\theta), ~~~ \text { and } \lim_{\theta->0} \frac{R(\theta)}{\theta} = 0
R(\theta)
 R(\theta)  = \sum_{k=2}^\infty \frac{\theta^k}{k!}
f_n(x)=\left(1+\frac xn\right)^n
f_n'(x)=\left(1+\frac xn\right)^{n-1}\sim e^x
 e^x=\lim_{n\to\infty}\left(1+\frac xn\right)^n 
 \lim_{n\to\infty}n\left(e^{x/n}-1\right)=x 
 \lim_{n\to\infty}n\left(x^{1/n}-1\right)=\log(x) 
 \lim_{v \to 0}\frac{a^v-1}{v} = a^v \log a\Bigg|_{v=0}=\log a 
